comment_data.body: My guess is that it's a concurrency issue with the large number of parallel processes. I just checked `runtests.py` and the refnanny is compiled inside of the test processes, not up-front from the main process. That seems worth changing.
I probably don't have enough CPU cores on my laptop to reproduce this in a reasonable way, so if you could give it a try on your side and create a PR from it…

I'm using 48 cores box so it may be a cause. 

Just tell me what I can do to help you.
I can quickluy add any patch to rpm spec file to test it and send you back results.

Hmm, no, it's already being built in separate directories:
https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/c0cd7fa100a91d52f0b350154e4d5ff9eb94aafe/runtests.py#L2386-L2391
(`WORKDIR` is specific to each shard, so is probably the temp directory.)
Can't say what's wrong then.
If you have any proposition of some diagnostic (even not a command but what should be targeted to prove disprove) please let me know.
Maybe the file that it's complaining about isn't being created in the temp directory but in some shared place? Could you verify if that's the case?

Presumably you have checked whether this happens without `-j` or with some lower `-j` number? Is it possible it's nothing to do with concurrency?

I'm a bit suspicious of `refnanny.cpython-38-x86_64-linux-gnu.so.lto.o`. When I look at my `TEST_TMP` directory afterwards the intermediate file is just called `refnanny.o` (but the .so file ends up with the full `cpython-38` label). I could well be completely wrong though.

Gosh it takes so long to pass test suite without parallelisation :)

Yes I can confirm that after disable parallel testing test suite passed successfully.
